node.text: On this episode of DMTV Milkshake, we talk to sculptor, designer, and #EllensNextGreatDesigner guest judge @iamfm, Fernando Mastrongelo. The New York-based artist makes furniture and large scale-sculptures and installations, often from natural materials like sand, salt, and silica. Click to hear why he thinks salt has a “life and death aspect to it” — and where his next big adventure will take him, following a cross-continent tour of South America on his motorcycle. \\\ #dmtvmilkshake #designmilktv

node.title: DMTV Milkshake: Celebrating (And Eulogizing) the Natural World

node.text: On this episode of DMTV Milkshake, we talk to Melodie Leung, associate director with @zahahadidarchitects. Here, we hear from the Chicago-bred, London-based architect on what she learned about the design process while working at the right hand of the great Zaha Hadid, her choice for the most beautifully composed building on Earth, and the architecture of the city of “hidden histories and lost rivers” that informs her work. \\\ #dmtvmilkshake #designmilktv

node.title: DMTV Milkshake: On Zaha Hadid, and Challenging the Design Process

node.text: For this week’s Milkshake, we spoke to @bimmawilliams, co-founder and host of the @claimastories podcast. Claima — ”claima” as in “claim a seat at the table” — is a podcast with a mission: to give young BIPOC creatives the inspiration, and roadmap, they need to make good on their ambitions. Bimma joins us from the road — specifically from, a custom-rigged 1993 Mitsubishi Delica Starwagon rechristened as “Storytella,” his mobile podcast studio during a 30-day, four-city tour of the West Coast. Here, he gives his best advice for young BIPOC creatives looking for professional advancement and shares a few of the stories that have moved him most. \\\ #dmtvmilkshake #designmilktv

node.title: DMTV Milkshake: Making Space for BIPOC Creatives

🔄 Rotate Your Device 🔄
Inside the Dallas studio of sculptor Dan Lam (@sopopomo), burbling, bubbling and bright works of art appear to move on their own. Ciao from Milano! Milan Design Week 2021 has officially commenced, but the flavor of its presentations will stay on our palates seasons-wide. With exhibitions spread across the city in showrooms, industrial sites, galleries, street-corner pop-ups, gardens, museums, and the most opulent of palazzos, we’ve taken a taste of it all and rounded up a bite-sized portion of some of the week’s most standout sources of inspiration. \\\ See our picks from Milan Design Week 2021 at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: We all have an inner child - playful, energetic, and restless - so designer Karel Matějka made a chair to suit. Restless is the latest object in Matějka’s L’Instabilité series, offering an unconventional look at movement in furniture design. The playful chair is organically shaped, and has the ability to swing as well as rotate on its axis, instantly transporting the sitter back to childhood play. \\\ At the link in bio, learn more about @matejka.karel's debut of Restless at this year's Milan Design Week. 🔗

node.text: Designed by Jim Olson of @olsonkundig, the Water Cabin is a 1,580-square-foot retreat with 180-degree views. The floating home resides on Portage Bay in Washington State with western red cedar siding inspired by weathered cabins. The vertical slats, hung irregularly like trees in a forest, will weather over the years while requiring minimal maintenance. Floor-to-ceiling sliding glass doors open to connect the interior with the exterior deck, thereby expanding the usable space. \\\ See more of the Water Cabin at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: In March of 2020, Brooklyn-based artist and founder of @thelawnsco design collective, Jess Murphy, set out to turn her artwork into wallpaper while she passed the time. Taking inspiration from a celebratory scene of dancing people in the film The Two Popes, Jess began by working with pre-pandemic live figure drawings. Thus the ‘Figures‘ wallpaper pattern was born, and became one of The Lawns’ six unique patterns inspired by quarantine movie benders, previous travels, rainy mornings and internet wormholes. \\\ At the link in bio, get a peek at how Jess designed the Figures wallpaper pattern for this month's Deconstruction. 🔗

node.text: On this episode of DMTV Milkshake, we talk to sculptor, designer, and #EllensNextGreatDesigner guest judge @iamfm, Fernando Mastrongelo. The New York-based artist makes furniture and large scale-sculptures and installations, often from natural materials like sand, salt, and silica. Click to hear why he thinks salt has a “life and death aspect to it” — and where his next big adventure will take him, following a cross-continent tour of South America on his motorcycle. \\\ #dmtvmilkshake #designmilktv

One of the new private residences on the property is this Bali-inspired penthouse, designed by Catalina Echavarria of @ceustudio. Boasting 360-degree ocean and skyline views of Miami, the Sky House spans almost 9,000 square feet, boasting 6,000 square feet of outdoor space with various areas for dining, lounging and entertaining. While the design has a luxe tropical modern feel, it also feels equally relaxing and healing. \\\ Read more about the Sky House at the link in bio. 🔗

The future of work will be at NeoCon 2021! Are tents the new cubicles? Boundary-breaking innovations like workplace tents and pergolas, flooring that incorporates biophilic patterns, plug-and-play smart technology, and dynamic furniture systems ideal for the flexible new office are among the exciting post-pandemic office solutions manufacturers will showcase at NeoCon, October 4-6 at theMART in Chicago. The show’s introductions and industry-leading talks will also address contract design across key sectors of Healthcare, Hospitality, Retail, Residential, Education, Public Space, and Government. \\\ Learn more and register at the link in bio.
